content.problemStatement:
**Array initialization** in Java means creating an array and giving it some values. An array is like a box that can hold many values of the same type (like numbers or words), all stored together in one place.

---

**Syntax:**
```java
dataType[] arrayName = {value1, value2, value3, ...}; //Static Initialization (Direct Initialization)
// dataType: This specifies the type of data the array will store (e.g., int, String, etc.).
// arrayName: This is the name of your array variable.
// Values: These are the initial values assigned to the array elements.
dataType[] arrayName = new dataType[size]; // Dynamic Initialization (Using the new keyword)
```
- **Static Initialization** assigns values at the time of declaration.
- **Dynamic Initialization** reserves memory first and values are assigned later.

---

**Example:**
```java
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Initialize an array with predefined values (static initialization)
        int[] staticArray = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

        System.out.println("Static Initialization:");

        // Declare and initialize an array dynamically with specified size
        int[] dynamicArray = new int[5];  

        System.out.println("Dynamic Initialization:");

        // Different data types of arrays

        // Boolean array
        boolean[] boolArray = {true, false, true};

        // Double array
        double[] doubleArray = {2.5, 3.14, 6.28};

        // Character array
        char[] charArray = {'A', 'B', 'C'};

        // String array
        String[] stringArray = {"Java", "Python", "C++"};
    }
}

